sec.p:
The dataset has missing values and it is addressed by use of Mean Imputation (MI) [12] whereby the missing feature value is substituted by the mean of the attribute that is calculated on the available data is given in Eq.~(\ref{eqn1}), where $x_{i}$ is the missing value, replaced by the mean of the available feature values
\begin{equation*}
x_{i}=\frac{\sum_{j=1}^{n} x_{j}}{n}, x_{i} \in \text { missing entries }
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

(2), where $\mu$ is the mean and $\sigma$ is the standard deviation of the feature, ensuring all features are on a similar scale for learning.
\begin{equation*}
x_{i}^{\prime}=\frac{x_{i}-\mu}{\sigma}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

The GOA [14] is based on the swarm behaviour of grasshoppers and it is popular in global optimization problems, such as feature selection in high-dimensional data. The swarm of grasshoppers represents each of the candidate solutions, i.e. a potential subset of features. The position of the $i$-th grasshopper at iteration $t, X_{i}(t)$, is updated based on three main components: social interaction, gravitational force, and wind advection is expressed in Eq.~(\ref{eqn3}).
\begin{equation*}
X_{i}(t+1)=S_{i}(t)+G_{i}(t)+A_{i}(t)
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

The social interaction $\left(S_{i}\right)$ component is used to model the attraction or repulsion of the grasshopper. It is computed as in Eq.~(\ref{eqn4}), in which, $d_{i j}=\left|X_{j}-X_{i}\right|$ is the distance between grasshoppers $i$ and $j, \hat{d}_{i j}=\frac{X_{j}-X_{i}}{d_{i j}}$ is the unit vector pointing from $i$ to $j, s(d)$ is the social force function is expressed in Eq.~(\ref{eqn5}), where, $f$ controls the intensity of attraction, and $l$ determines the attractive length scale.
\begin{equation*}
\begin{aligned}
& S_{i}=\sum_{j=1, j \neq i}^{N} s\left(d_{i j}\right) \hat{d}_{i j} \\
& s(d)=f e^{-d / l}-e^{-d}
\end{aligned}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

Gravitational force ($G_{i}$) is also provided with gravity that pulls downwards towards the centre of the search space is given in Eq.~(\ref{eqn6}), where, $g$ is the gravitational constant and $\hat{e}_{g}$ is a unit vector pointing toward the center of gravity.
\begin{equation*}
G_{i}=g \hat{e}_{g}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

Wind advection $\left(A_{i}\right)$ is estimated as an external bias in a particular direction to diversify the search search is given in Eq.~(\ref{eqn7}), where $u$ is the wind speed and $\hat{e}_{w}$ is the wind direction vector
\begin{equation*}
A_{i}=u \hat{e}_{w}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

The proposed SAGWOA aims at maximizing the classification performance and minimizing the number of features. The fitness function is defined as in Eq.~(\ref{eqn8}), where; $\operatorname{Accuracy}\left(X_{i}\right)$ is the classification accuracy achieved using the selected features $F_{i},\left|F_{i}\right|$ is the number of selected features, $\left|F_{\text {total }}\right|$ is the total number of features, $\alpha$ and $\beta$ are weighting factors controlling the trade-off between accuracy and feature reduction.
\begin{equation*}
\operatorname{Fitness}\left(X_{i}\right)=\alpha \cdot \operatorname{Accuracy}\left(X_{i}\right)-\beta \cdot \frac{\left|F_{i}\right|}{\left|F_{\text {total }}\right|}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

To further encourage sparsity, an additional penalty term included is given in Eq.~(\ref{eqn9}), where, $x_{i k} \in\{0,1\}$ indicates whether feature $k$ is selected in solution $i$, and $\gamma \in<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref0">[0], <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref1">[1]$ penalizes larger subsets.
\begin{equation*}
\operatorname{Fitness}\left(X_{i}\right)=\alpha \cdot \operatorname{Accuracy}\left(X_{i}\right)-\beta \cdot \frac{\left|F_{i}\right|}{\left|F_{\text {total }}\right|}-\gamma \cdot
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

During iterations, each grasshopper updates its feature subset probabilistically is given in Eq.~(\ref{eqn10}), in which, $\sigma$ is the sigmoid function used to map continuous positions to binary selections for feature subsets is given in Eq.~(\ref{eqn11}).
\begin{equation*}
\begin{aligned}
& x_{i k}(t+1)=\left\{\begin{array}{lc}
1, & \text { if } \operatorname{rand}()<\sigma\left(X_{i}(t+1)\right) \\
0, & \text { otherwise }
\end{array}\right. \\
& \sigma(X)=\frac{1}{1+e^{-X}}
\end{aligned}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

In proposed SAGWOA, the position of a candidate solution (feature subset) is updated according to the Eq.~(\ref{eqn12}), where; $\vec{X}^{*}(t)$ is the best solution found so far, $\vec{X}(t)$ is the current candidate solution, in which, and $\vec{C}$ are coefficient vectors controlling the search behavior, defined as in Eq.~(\ref{eqn13}).
\begin{equation*}
\begin{aligned}
& \vec{X}(t+1)=\vec{X}^{*}(t)-\vec{A} \cdot\left|\vec{C} \cdot \vec{X}^{*}(t)-\vec{X}(t)\right| \\
& \vec{A}=2 a \cdot \vec{r}-a, \vec{C}=2 \cdot \vec{r}
\end{aligned}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

In order to make goal-oriented and weight-oriented contributions adaptively balanced, SAGWOA presents a weight factor $w(t)$ as varying the contribution of global and local search according to iteration number is given in Eq.~(\ref{eqn5}), where; $\vec{X}_{G O A}(t+1)$ is the position updated by GOA (global exploration), $\vec{X}_{\text {WOA }}(t+1)$ is the position updated by WOA (local exploitation), in which, $w(t)$ decreases linearly is given in Eq.~(\ref{eqn16}).
\begin{equation*}
\begin{aligned}
& \vec{X}_{i}(t+1)=w(t) \cdot \vec{X}_{G O A}(t+1)+(1-w(t)) \\
& \vec{X}_{W O A}(t+1) \\
& \quad w(t)=1-\frac{t}{T_{\max }}
\end{aligned}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

The feature selection is a binary optimization problem, and hence the continuous positions are coded to binary values through a sigmoid function given in Eq.~(\ref{eqn17}), where, $x_{i k}$ indicates whether feature $k$ is selected in solution $i$.
\begin{equation*}
\quad x_{i k}(t+1)=\left\{\begin{array}{lc}
1, & \text { if } \operatorname{rand}()<\sigma\left(X_{i}(t+1)\right) \\
0, & \text { otherwise }
\end{array}, \sigma(X)=\right.
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

The subsets of the hybrid-selected features are tested with the help of the fitness function of the classification accuracy and the feature reduction is given in Eq.~(\ref{eqn18}), where; $\left|F_{i}\right|$ is the number of selected features, $\left|F_{\text {total }}\right|$ is the total feature count, and $\alpha, \beta \in<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref0">[0], <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref1">[1]$ balance accuracy and subset size.
\begin{equation*}
\operatorname{Fitness}\left(X_{i}\right)=\alpha \cdot \operatorname{Accuracy}\left(X_{i}\right)-\beta \cdot \frac{\left|F_{i}\right|}{\left|F_{\text {total }}\right|}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

After optimal feature selection using proposed SAGWOA, the reduced feature vector $X=\left\{x_{1}, x_{2}, \ldots, x_{n}\right\}$ is encoded into quantum states to enable quantum-inspired learning through VQC [16]. Two commonly used encoding schemes are adopted: amplitude encoding and angle (rotation) encoding. In amplitude encoding, the classical features are represented in the amplitudes of a quantum state is given in Eq.~(\ref{eqn19}), which subjected to the normalization constraint is given in Eq.~(\ref{eqn20}).
\begin{equation*}
\begin{aligned}
&| \psi\rangle=\sum_{i=1}^{n} x_{i}|i\rangle \\
& \sum_{i=1}^{n}\left|x_{i}\right|^{2}=1
\end{aligned}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

This encoding allows an $n$-dimensional feature vector to be represented using $\log _{2}(n)$ qubits, enabling compact representation of high-dimensional data. In angle encoding, every classical feature is encoded to an angle of rotation of a quantum gate is expressed in Eq.~(\ref{eqn21}), where $f(\cdot)$ is a scaling function (e.g., linear or min-max scaling).
\begin{equation*}
\theta_{i}=f\left(x_{i}\right)
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

The encoded state is generated using rotation gates is given in Eq.~(\ref{eqn22}),
\begin{equation*}
|\psi\rangle=\prod_{i=1}^{n} R_{y}\left(\theta_{i}\right)|0\rangle
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

notably, VQC uses a parametrized quantum circuit (PQC) to carry out classification. The encoded quantum state is processed using a variational unitary operation $U(\theta)$ is given in Eq.~(\ref{eqn23}), where, $\theta$ represents trainable parameters optimized during learning.
\begin{equation*}
|\phi\rangle=U(\theta)|\psi\rangle
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

The output is obtained by measuring quantum observables is given in Eq.~(\ref{eqn24}),
\begin{equation*}
y=\langle\phi| M|\phi\rangle=\text { measure }(U(\theta)|\psi\rangle)
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

The parameters $\theta$ are updated by minimizing a loss function, typically defined as in Eq.~(\ref{eqn25}),
\begin{equation*}
\mathcal{L}=\frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^{N}\left(y_{i}-\widehat{y}_{i}\right)^{2}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

The QSVM [17] is a machine that works in Hilbert space computing a quantum kernel, to estimate the similarity between encoded feature vectors is given in Eq.~(\ref{eqn27}).
\begin{equation*}
K\left(x_{i}, x_{j}\right)=\left|\left\langle\psi\left(x_{i}\right) \mid \psi\left(x_{j}\right)\right\rangle\right|^{2}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

The kernel matrix $K$ is then used in the SVM optimization problem is expressed in Eq.~(\ref{eqn28}),
\begin{equation*}
\min _{\alpha} \frac{1}{2} \sum_{i, j} \alpha_{i} \alpha_{j} y_{i} y_{j} K\left(x_{i}, x_{j}\right)-\sum_{i} \alpha_{i}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

Which subjected to the expression given in Eq.~(\ref{eqn29}),
\begin{equation*}
\sum_{i} \alpha_{i} y_{i}=0,0 \leq \alpha_{i} \leq C
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

Besides, a CNN [18]) is used to improve the learning of representations and then classification using QSVM. The CNN derives hierarchical and spatial features is given in Eq.~(\ref{eqn30}), where $H$ denotes deep feature maps.
\begin{equation*}
H=C N N(X)
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

The extracted features are then fed into the QSVM for final classification is computed by Eq.~(\ref{eqn31}).
\begin{equation*}
\hat{y}=\operatorname{QSVM}(H)
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}
